  "doc_id": "23072",
  "text": "GCTs are typically found in the epiphyseal area of long bones and have a predilection for females in their third decade [CITATION_1] . These tumors are usually benign in nature but can be locally aggressive, recur, and occasionally undergo pulmonary metastasis [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . About 4% of all primary bone tumors are GCTs, with approximately 2% of all GCTs occurring in the head and neck region [CITATION_4] . Most often GCTs in the head neck region occur in the sphenoid, ethmoid, or temporal bones and very rarely in the hyoid bone and cartilaginous framework of the larynx [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Wessely reported the first case of a laryngeal GCT in 1940 [CITATION_7] . Including our case and based on our literature search, there have been an additional 42 reported cases (Table 1 ) .",
